Now is it not clear, on a close comparison, that Lollius, being a young' man of rank, the son of a vir consularis, hot and high-spirited, was liable to offend by want of due com'- plaisance? With his natural brusquerie and his fits of con- tradictory or unaccommodating humour, he was the most unlikely man in Rome (scurrantis speciem praebere) to be mistaken for a sycophant. Scaeva, on the other hand, timid apparently and somewhat necessitous himself, with relatives perhaps ill provided for, while he required encouragement to undertake the office of living with the great, might stand no less in need of delicate cantion, how to improve his for- 'tunes as the comes (v. 52) to a rex (v, 43) without meanness and without importunity.
